<br>
I think Verant realizes that with each expansion they only delay the inevitable - that the high end players will max out the game.  First, raise the level cap from 50 - 60.  Then, create the faction work required to succeed in Velious and the Sleeper story.  Now, it is Alternate Advancement Points.<br>
<br>
But, what happens once people get their all of the titles available to them, and have a bunch of AA points?  They (VI) has once again only delayed the inevitable.<br>
<br>
At the same time, there is a *ton* of content currently in the game, enough to keep the average casual player satisfied for a very, very long time.<br>
<br>
So, why not create &quot;Expert Classes&quot; and zones specifically for them?  Say, for example, that you need to be level 60 and have the highest AA title.  Then you can become a 'new class' - it solves the &quot;no skills over 255&quot; problem because you start over at Level 1 with all of your skills at 1, but the skills are based off of new tables that start where the old ones leave off.<br>
<br>
And new zones.  Similar to how you have to be 45+ to hit the planes, you have to be a new class to hit these new zones.  &quot;Enhanced classes&quot; would only get XP or AA points in the new zones - everything in the existing zones becomes trivial.  <br>
<br>
As I said, the game currently has a ton of content.  Casual players could continue to play the current game - many many people would be perfectly happy exploring all of the current zones, and most will never reach their highest AA title.  And those that do want new challenges would have &quot;special&quot; content just for them.  It would allow those people, and those guilds, to feel challenged and elite while at the same time allowing the people who don't want to advance to that level enjoy the game as it currently stands. <p><center><img src="http://www.darke.net/journalpix/bearne.jpg"><BR>
